column20:
Code to read lines via fgets() with a signal handler in effect for interrupts, set via sigaction().
The code shows some of the lengths you have to go to if you are to avoid using printf() et al inside a signal handler function and yet vaguely simulate using it.  The implemented functions are defective in that they do not take or check the buffer length.  This is safe in context, but theoretically, the functions should be passed a length or end pointer and should ensure no overflow.
Also trying formatting the pull request more formally — not using much Markdown, but at least formatting the request.

column13: SO 2088-9460: Revise build and lose system-headers directory
column20:
The system-headers directory and its checked-in contents (3 one-line files) really wasn't needed.  The makefile has been revised to build create and populate the directory on demand.  The example code includes <algorithm> too (the original did not).  And the main soq-tail.mk file now removes directories listed in ${OUTDIRS} parallel to removing files listed in ${OUTFILES}.  The system-headers directory is therefore ignored, now.
The makefile assumes that mkdir -p creates a directory if necessary and is silent (and successful) if the directory already exists, though a marginally more complex set of rules could use plain mkdir if someone was really worried about portability.

column13: src/matrices: vlamat.c - set array dimensions from command line
column20:
Primary change allows vlamat.c to be run with 3 arguments to control the size of the array.  If the 3 arguments are N1, N2, N3 (each in the range 1..99), then the program will create an array of size N1xN2, another of size N2xN3, and a result matrix of size N1xN3.  If there aren't 3 arguments, the size will be N1 = 3, N2 = 5, N3 = 4.
Also tweak content of README file.

column20:
Add a bunch of URLs to the README.md file, referencing Wikipedia, Ben Pfaff's writings, Coding Horror blog, other SO questions.
Modify genshuffle.c — add a simulation of the 'shuffle 3-element array' code from The Danger of Naivete blog entry on Coding Horror to demonstrate that the shuffle is reasonably unbiassed.  Note that if the program is run with an argument, that is used as a seed.  Testing run repeatedly using:
./genshuffle $(randseed -b 4)

(where randseed -b 4 returns 4 bytes hex-encoded read from /dev/urandom).  The results were satisfying to the eye: repeated sets of one million trials produced counts in the range 165782 .. 167343 for the 6 permutations, which is absolutely not the biassed distribution in 'The Danger' article.

column13: SO 4828-2480 plus support work in libsoq
column20:
Various enhancements to original SO 4828-2480 work — command line configuration of threads and cycles, and also revised (more complex) code to detect joinable threads.  This requires cooperation between the main thread (waiting on a condition) and the child threads (signalling on the condition when exiting).
Also enhanced stderr.[ch] in libsoq:

Use flockfile() and funlockfile() if available to make the writing coherent.
Add fflush() to ensure that even if the error stream is fully logged, the error messages are written to disk.
Add new (but previously predicted) err_settimeformat() and err_gettimeformat() functions to allow configuration of time format.
Add new config.h header — accurate for macOS Sierra 10.12.3, probably good for most Linux variants.
Add CFLAGS += -DHAVE_CONFIG_H to library makefile.

And, of course:

Use the new functions in code for SO 4828-2480.

column20:
Extending the work previously done accidentally on the master branch.  This code now seems to work pretty well.
It is now using the RationalInt type (using the synonym Rational) from SO-3388-7484.  There are still issues with Phased Test Harness not being available.  The rational.c and rational.h files, plus test.rational.c were extracted from the code in GitHub,, and pushed under RCS as usual.  They'll be migrated in due course to GitHub.
Using the Rational arithmetic turned out to be pleasingly straight-forward, though the function ri_neg() had to be added.  The RI_ZERO() and RI_ONE() macros need review.  Those constants are remarkably important; it isn't wholly clear that's the best way to handle them (and the code is only in polynomial.c — not in the main rational.c or rational.h code).  I also needed a method to get rid of the forced positive signs in the rational printing.

The rational.c and rational.h files, plus test.rational.c were extracted from the code in GitHub,, and pushed under RCS as usual.  They'll be migrated in due course to GitHub.
Using the Rational arithmetic turned out to be pleasingly straight-forward, though the function ri_neg() had to be added.  The RI_ZERO() and RI_ONE() macros need review.  Those constants are remarkably important; it isn't wholly clear that's the best way to handle them (and the code is only in polynomial.c — not in the main rational.c or rational.h code).  I also needed a method to get rid of the forced positive signs in the rational printing.

column20:
Two sets of changes — I should probably work out how to get GitHub to take the two sets separately, but … oh, well!
New question SO 4555-1869: pthread synchronization issue.  Various programs.  pth11 is the OP's code with minimal changes to make it compile under my stringent compilation options.  It does not run successfully, deadlocking because the conditions are signalled before the waiters are waiting.  pth13 works using nanosleep() for 10 µs to get things synchronized.  pth17 works without sleeping at all — and has extensive error checking added.  pth19 uses functions to do the work and can be run requesting 2..20 threads.  Compared with what would be required to make pth17 work with even 3 threads, the factorization into functions is a magnificent performance benefit.
Old question SO 3388-7484: updates to the code to match the question's requirements and naming.  The code in so.33887484.md isn't an exact match to the code in so.33887484.h, ratcalc.c, so.33887484.c.  Should adopt technology from SO 0143-3204 (extern variables) to create a version of the answer from text plus embedding the source code.  That's TBD (not least because the management code (insert-code.pl) would need to be moved, presumably to src/scripts).

column20:
The question asks about epoll(), which is specific to Linux.  This code was developed on a Mac running macOS High Sierra 10.13.2 where epoll() is not an option.  This code has not (yet) been submitted as an answer.
fifo-rdr-41.c
Code to read from a FIFO, repeatedly.
Default usage has no arguments; -h provides help, -r reopens the FIFO when EOF is detected; -w opens the FIFO for writing (but never writes to it) so EOF is never detected.
fifo-wrt-41.c
Code to write to a FIFO, a few times.
It sends a random number of messages, each of which is a random number of bytes long but consists of upper-case letters.  It pauses for a random time before sending each message, and also before it closes the FIFO.
It has no options, but configuring the random times would be an obvious option to use, as would adding options to send the contents of a file, etc.
What they demonstrate
However, the pair of programs demonstrates that:

You can't complete opening a FIFO for reading until there's a writer.
You can't complete opening a FIFO for writing until there's a reader.
While a process has the FIFO open for writing, a reader will block waiting for input, even if the process is itself.
If a reader gets EOF (0 bytes read), it can close the FIFO and reopen it; the open() call will wait until a new writer opens the FIFO.
If there is no writer, the reader will hang in a busy loop continually reading no bytes, unless the code takes step to avoid it.

Notes
The code includes a random_milli_nap() function which takes a minimum and maximum nap time in milliseconds and waits for a random time in that interval.  It uses rand(); it would not be hard to upgrade it to use a separate PRNG (so as not to interfere with other random number sequences).
The code includes some semi-useful signal handling.  It uses stderr.c and stderr.h from src/libsoq because that simplifies error reporting.

column20:
SO 3994-9116:


trie89.c
Identify which dictionary is used, and change the default to alt.words.01.


SO 4997-3664


trie-search13.c
Load one or more dictionaries of words, and then analyze word lists from files or from command line word arguments.  This has basic search functionality, recognizing concatenated sequences of known words from  the dictionaries that are loaded.


trie-split59.c
An extension of trie-search13.c which recognizes unknown words, and skips over that material to find more known words after the unknown. This uses the 'array of strings' code from aoscopy.[ch] in the libsoq directory.  This code does not manage to distinguish between words and non-words after the list is processed, but does handle spaces between words — so it can process README.md, unlike trie-search13.c.


trie-split67.c
An extension of trie-split67.c which records the classification of strings into non-alphabetic, known word and unknown word.  This uses the 'array of memory blocks' code from aommngd.[ch], which was developed to handle this use case.


alt.words.01 — a smallish set of words with common prefixes.


alt.words.02 — a larger set of words, with all initial letters of the alphabet present.


alt.words.03 — some concatenated numeric words.


alt.words.04 — words list for some of the more complex concatenated words found in the README.md file, etc.


alt.words.05 — adds 'a' and 'an' as words.


alt.words.06 — various complex concatenated words.


Running:
trie-split67 -d words.numeric -d alt.words.04 -d alt.words.05 -w alt.words.06

reveals some problems with the greedy word searching algorithm.  For example, thereignofcharles is recognized as words there, i, and non-word g, word no, non-word f, word charles. when it is a part of a longer string.  Similarly, adozenpeopleandtheirthreescoredonkeysateonegrossofbagels is split correctly, but thedonkeysateditsappetite is split into the, donkeys, ate, non-word d, its, appetite — instead of the, donkey, sated, its, appetite.
Fixing this would be trickier and has not been attempted.
Valgrind check shows that the code is not leaking.

column13: SO 5100-4470: Why it is important to close unused pipe file descriptors.
column20:
Code showing why it is important to close unused ends of pipes, both the
read and the write ends of the pipe.
When invoked without any arguments, the programs (fork13 and fork29)
fail to complete; one of the processes is jammed because it is either
reading or writing on a pipe where the only process with the
complementary end of the pipe open is the same process.
When invoked with arguments, the pipe descriptors are properly closed
and the pipeline completes (not always successfully — the writing
process gets a SIGPIPE signal — but without jamming indefinitely).

column13: src/Primes/isprime.c: Add extra prime tester isprime4().
column20:
Surprisingly, isprime2() now seems to be fastest, faster even than
isprime3(), and isprime4() is about the same as isprime3().  The
differences between isprime1-4 are fairly small — time range
currently 12.5-14.7, but the delta between 2 and the others is just
under 1 second, and the difference between the others is less than 0.1
second.  The actual times and number of primes found depends on the
seed.

column20:
A 'basic' solution to the problem posed in SO 5631-4784 "How to chunk shell script input by time, not by size?".  It isn't a trivial problem to solve.  The code has 3 implementations using alarm(2) (compile with -DUSE_ALARM, setitimer(2) (compile with -DUSE_SETITIMER), and using timer_create(2) et al (default compilation mode).  On Linux, you need the -lrt library; it is specified by default.  On a Mac (up to macOS 10.14.5 Mojave), there is no timer_create() and there is no library for -lrt.  So, for a Mac, compile using make UFLAGS=-DUSE_SETITIMER LDLIB2= (for Linux, just make is sufficient).
You will need the library code from src/libsoq too.

column13: SO 4295-4541 — Sorting odd or even valued elements of an array
column20:
The perceived problem is to take an array of integers, both odd and even values,
and to sort either the odd or the even values into ascending order, while not
moving the values with the other parity in the array.
The code to do so using an auxilliary array as big as the data array (but not
copying the data into that array) is developed incrementally.
The code to do so without the auxilliary array is also shown, but it is subtle
and slow and not recommended.

column20:
Provides a generic style guideline message for people using spaces
around the C dot . and arrow -> operators.
Configurable between using dot (-d) or arrow (-a, default) between members.
Default list is "ptr member" but longer lists or alternative names are
command line arguments (but you must cite at least two names).
There's no provision for variable->ptrmember.member->data with a mixed
sequence of dot and arrow operators.
That gets tricky.
Maybe -r 'variable->ptrmember.member->data' would work, with the
script spacing out the operators and compressing the spaces.
